3.1 Data and Study Area

This analysis uses 2020 Zoopla Property Sale Data, which is anonymized, managed, and sub-licensed on the behalf for research purposes by the Urban Big Data Center (UBDC) at Glasgow. The data has been accessed through the sub-license agreement and the UBDC access agreement. As one of the UK’s leading providers of property data for consumers and professionals, Zoopla owns a massive dataset containing information about the property price, location, and “hard” property features such as the number of floors and bedrooms. More importantly, it provides characteristic descriptions and bullets for most property listings, which may have unobserved “soft” characteristics that impact the property value. 2020 Zoopla Property Sale Data has over 400000 property listing records with 50 columns in London. After dropping duplicated records and listings without basic housing characteristics information, 138587 records are still kept for this analysis.

The research area focuses on London, the largest real estate market in the UK. Since previous studies have shown that geographic location is a dominant variable and dramatically impacts the regression results, this study will blur geographic location to highlight the impact of textual housing characteristics on housing prices. Instead of using boroughs or more precise location information, this study assigns properties to five subregions based on boroughs (Figure 3.2). In addition, the fuzzy spatial information is hoped to avoid overfitting the model in a specific city and make the model more applicable in other regions.

Figure 3.2 Study Area: London Sub-regions. According to London Plan Consultation (2009), Greater London can be divided into five sub regions: Central, North, East, South and West. The latest version is released in 2011.

3.2 Data Preprocessing and Exploring Data Analysis (EDA)

Although the Zoopla dataset contains 50 columns, most columns are information about agents and administrative divisions. There are also columns that record changes in the same housing characteristics over different time periods. For example, Zoopla details multiple prices for a property, including the price at which the property appeared on the first and last day, the lowest and highest price, and the unique value of price changes observed during the listing period. However, the study does not require so many prices, so only the last day's price that could be considered transaction prices is selected. After removing redundant and irrelevant attribute columns, 8 variables remained (Table 3.1). It is worth mentioning that while the Zoopla dataset contains description columns that describe attributes using paragraphs, this study uses a bullet column instead, which already highlights the main features of attributes from the descriptions.

Table 3.1 Selected Zoopla housing features for analysis and their descriptions

With the ultimate purpose of constructing regression models to predict the housing price in London, the price_last column is the dependent variable. Using the logarithmically transforming variables is a common and effective way to handle the non-linear relationship to fit a linear regression model (Benoit, 2011). This analysis thus uses a logged price to transform the highly skewed price distribution into a more approximately normal one. The un-logged price is highly right-skewed with a value of 16.84. After logarithm transformation, the skew value is down to 0.97. Outliers are also detected, and there is a total of 6155 outliers. However, most of them have been kept, considering that costly or cheap housing prices could also exist in the real world. Only properties with 0 value are considered extremely unreasonable and are kicked out.

Figure 3.3 Price distribution before and after logarithm

In addition to the dependent variable, the independent variables also need to be pre-processed. After checking four numerical variables, bed, floor, bathroom, and reception, the number of bathrooms is found problematic. 11393 records show 0 bathrooms. However, if checking the house description in bullet, many of them do have bathrooms but no records in the num_bath_max column. One possible explanation is that these lists left out the number of bathrooms when entering the data into the database. This study decided not to use the record of properties with 0 bathrooms to ensure the accuracy of the data.

On the other hand, categorical features, including property types and sub-regions, are transformed into dummy variables to capture the influence of categorical variables in regression analysis (Trochim, n.d., Yip and Tsang, 2007). Although there are 33 varieties of property types, most properties are grouped into a few limited property types. Therefore, this study only selects major property types with more than 1000 records. In the end, seven property types remained: End terrace house, Flat, Studio, Maisonette, Semi-detached house, Detached house, and Terraced house.

