3.3 Extracting and quantifying keywords with NLP analysis

After cleaning the numerical and categorical variables, it is time to deal with bullet column and get textual variables. Though the bullet already represents the key characteristics of each property, it still needs to be cleaned and analysed to extract the most meaningful and iconic keywords from a bunch of textual information. Natural language processing (NLP) supports the entire text mining procedure.

3.3.1 Text transformations: cleaning bullet description

Text pre-processing is a necessary process before extracting keywords from bullet. Texts usually contain lots of noise and uninformative words such as HTML tags and advertisements that make the text hard to understand. In addition, these words cause the curse of dimensionality because each word is treated as one dimension in conventional texting mining techniques such as TF-IDF (Haddi, Liu, and Shi, 2013). Thus, reducing the text's noise must be done to improve the textual analysis. The text pre-processing could vary depending on various text and tasks, and the whole process is called textual transformation (Feinerer, Hornik, and Meyer, 2008).

For this study, words in bullets are converted to lowercase, and any HTML tags or accented characters are removed. Abbreviations are expanded by using related contraction libraries. All Arabic numerals have been removed, taking into account that keywords should have generic characteristics that do not contain specific year or quantity information. For stopwords, the nltk stopword corpus is used as a list of standard stopwords, with some variations related to specific characteristics of the property text. Characters such as ft, sq, area, square, and approx are considered specific attribute words that frequently occur in the text but do not provide valuable information. These words are manually added to the list of stop words, alongside numeric characters. "No" and “off” has been removed from the NLTK stopword list because it changes the entire meaning of the housing characteristics. In addition, each word's part-of-speech (POS) is identified and tagged. Some certain POS words that only contain sole noun character (e.g., bedroom or bedrooms) are removed. Finally, in addition to the necessary commas, extra whitespace tabs and punctuation are removed to tidy up the remaining text. Lemmatization and stemming, referring to transforming a word's inflectional forms into a common base form, are popular in most text transformation processes (Yadav, 2020; Selva, 2018). However, this analysis does not include stemming or lemmatization because these procedures would confuse some housing domain words such as parking and parks.  Table 3.2 gives a sample of a text transformation process.

Table 3.2 a sample text transformation applied to the bullet description

Text transformation tidies up bulleted text and reduces unnecessary information. If all the house characteristics in the property listing are unnecessary, it would end up with a blank cleaned text. These empty property listings are removed.

3.3.2 Measuring overall word frequency and getting preliminary classifications

The next step is to examine the overall word frequency in the cleaned text and find out the few most frequently mentioned aspects in the bullet description. The logic is that if a word is frequently mentioned in many properties, it is at least a thing that consumers value or the property agent think matter, which may impact property values.

Document-term matrix (DTM) and Term Frequency/Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF) are the most popular frequency approaches to measure word frequency. DTM tracks the frequency of terms that occur in a collection of documents, while TF-IDF is based on DTM but adds the weight of inverse document frequency (Salton and Buckley, 1988). However, the length of DTM or TF-IDF vectors is equal to the size of the vocabulary. When dealing with massive corpus, these approaches would suffer from the curse of dimensionality and become memory-inefficient (Yun, Ling, and Yong-cheng, 2005). Different Python platforms and modules have various calculating speeds, so the choice of python modules would become crucial.

This study compared the functions in Sklean and NLTK and found that NLTK has much faster computing power. Therefore, to speed up the calculation process, this study uses NLTK and its text and collocation module (NLTK, n.d.). The Text vocab function can quickly return the frequency distribution of a single word in the corpus according to the principle of DTM. In addition, the collocation module allows identifying collocation in which words frequently appear consecutively. Each set of words is scored to determine the relative likelihood of each consecutive word sequence in the text as a collocation. Table 3.3 lists the top 15 most frequently occurred single words, two-word collocations (Bigram), and three-word collocations (Trigram).

Table 3.3 Top 15 most frequently occurred single word, two-word scollocation (Bigram), and three-word collocation (Trigram) in the bullet description

The frequent occurred single word are mostly functional zoning of space such as 'room', 'garden', 'kitchen', 'reception', 'bedroom', and 'bathroom', or some explicitly orientated nouns such as 'chain', 'location' and 'station'. However, without contextual information, a single word is not enough to explain the housing features.

For example, 'room' is a pretty general word. However, if combing Bigram and Trigram, 'room' is found mainly following 'reception', so 'reception' or 'reception room' should be selected as the correct valued feature, but 'room' is not.

The word 'parking' appears in the single word list, revealing its importance recognized by property agents and custermers. 'street parking' in the Bigram seems to enhance the importance of parking. However, the collocation 'off street parking' in Trigram reminds us that not all property descriptions containing 'street parking' means parking a vehicle along a roadside. It could be the opposite meaning. In this situation, more types of parking should be explored.

The word 'garden' repeatedly appears in the table with various adjective modifiers. For sure, 'garden' is a valued feature that may not be simply classified as having a garden or do not have a garden. More explorations should be made to divide 'garden' into sub-level categories.

After analyzing and combining the common words and collocations above single word, Bigram, and Trigram, this study finally picks 11 most frequently mentioned features of property description, some of which need further classification. The preliminary classified features are displayed in Table 3.4.

Table 3.4 preliminary classified housing features extracted from the bullet description

The characteristics of the 11 preliminary classifications can be divided into five aspects: property ownership, property purchase process, housing characteristics, functional zoning, and neighbourhood and location. Except for "double room", all functional compartments are mentioned multiple times with various adjective modifiers and need further classification. In addition, the words "transport connection", "location", "station", "closed", and "local amenities" are considered to represent the overall characteristics of a good neighbourhood and location, as agents always tend to use positive descriptions.

3.3.3 Sub-level classifications and getting dummy keywords variables

Except for the "double bedroom", all functional divisions require further exploration, dividing them into sub-classifications. First, this study extracts all modifiers for each keyword "garden", "reception", "kitchen" and "parking" separately. The Python Re module, which provides regular expression support, is used to find property listings that contain these keywords. A function is defined to extract the modifiers associated with each keyword from the cleaned bullet column and map them to the new column. Table 3.5 provides example results for extracting garden modifiers. For each cleaned bullet description, if it contains a keyword "garden" in any phrase separated by a comma, the word before "garden" will be extracted as modifiers. On the other hand, if the cleaned bullet description does not mention the keyword, the new column will remain empty and marked "None".

Table 3.5 samples of extracting Garden modifiers from the cleaned bullet description

Then, TF-IDF is used to examine and rank the frequency distribution of modifiers for each keyword. The top 30 modifier phrases for each keyword were picked, compared, and categorized into several sub-levels features based on word similarity. In order to check the word similarity, this study initially attempted to use a pre-trained Word2Vec model to create word vectors. Compared to traditional bag models such as TF-IDF, which represent each word in the corpus by a large sparse vector, Word2Vec uses word embedding techniques to create low-dimensional vectors in a continuous vector space (Mikolov, 2013). It is advanced in checking the contextual similarity and semantic relationship between words. Words with high contextual similarity are closer in the vector space, enabling similarity-based word classification (Zhang, 2022). However, it was quickly discovered that Word2Vec was not suitable for this study. The cleaned bullet description itself cannot provide contextual information, so a pre-trained Word2Vec model must be introduced. However, existing pre-trained models only provide vectors for every single word. Modifiers with consecutive word sequences, such as "lovely south facing rear garden", do not exist in existing word vector models. Therefore, after careful consideration, this study decided not to use Word2vec but a human decision process to manually check word similarity and group words into meaningful sub-level categories. The following diagram demonstrates the sample logistic behind the sub-level classification (Figure 3.5).

Figure 3.5 Schematic diagram of the logistic behind sub-level classification decision

In the above three example garden modifiers, words with similar meanings will be grouped together as sub-level garden features. For example, "beautiful" and "stunning" are both positive descriptive adjectives with no special meaning. So these words will be grouped together. On the other hand, "rear" and "front" describe different types of gardens, so they should be divided into two separate categories. There is no fixed number of subclasses per keyword. It is entirely up to the semantic meaning of the modifier.

These sub-level classifications combined with the house features preliminarily classified in the previous step form the complete house characteristics. That is all valuable information extracted from the bullet attribute description. Using regular expression to check each property listing, if the property listing one feature, this feature in this property listing is assigned a value of 1. Otherwise, it is 0. If one property listing contains multiple features, it will have a score of one across multiple features. Finally, this study gets all dummy housing characteristic variables. The details of final variables will be presented and explained in the result section.

3.4 Regression models: evaluating the impacts of keyword features

The last part of this section is to build machine learning regression models to examine the impact of these keyword features. To accurately assess the impact, this study will apply different regression models and run each of them twice: once using the Zoopla variable without extracting keyword features from bullet, and once adding all keyword features based on the first run. The R-squared difference before and after adding keywords can explain the degree of influence of keyword features on attribute values. The more the R-squared increases, the greater the impact of keyword features on home values.

The purpose of running different models is to account for the bias between models, as different models may get different coefficients of variables. Comparing the commonalities and differences of models can identify the most influential keyword features. In consideration of the limitations of the conventional hedonic regression model, this study adopts two regression models: Lasso and GBDT, derived from the hedonic regression model. While GWR is also a powerful technique for examining local spatial relationships, this study focuses on the global relationships between keyword features and property values. Therefore, GWR regression will not be used in this study.

The dataset is divided into train and test datasets in an 80%: 20% ratio. The training dataset refers to the sample of data used to fit the model, while the test dataset is the dataset used to provide a final evaluation of model fit on the training dataset.

3.4.1 Lasso Regression

The Python library scikit-learn provides a Lasso linear model, which is applied to this study (sklearn.linear_model.Lasso, 2022). The Lasso regression model shrinks some regression coefficients that do not contribute much to the prediction task. The coefficients of these unimportant variables are reduced to zero by adding an L1 (absolute value of magnitude) penalty to the loss function. Feature selection is performed after shrinkage, where each non-zero value is selected for the regression model.

