3.4.2 Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost)

As previous literature introduces, ensemble learning is a machine learning technique that combines several base models built with a given learning algorithm to produce one effective optimal prediction (Lutins, 2017). Boosting is the main class of ensemble learning, that boosting algorithms train models sequentially (What is Boosting, 2021). A series of ensemble learners are constructed, and in each new model iteration, the weights of data are redistributed to improve the predictive. Through the successive steps in the learning process, the boosting optimizes the prediction performance.

This study used an optimized distributed gradient boosting library, XGBoost, an open-source library designed for computational speed and scale. It runs much faster than existing popular solutions on a single machine and can scale to billions of examples in distributed or memory-limited settings (Truong et al., 2020). The XGBRegressor model from XGBoost is firstly run with default hyperparameters. However, the model performance varies in data splitting and setting of hyperparameters. Thus, to avoid overfitting and randomness, the study used cross-validation to improve the models' performance. Half of the text dataset is split into a validation dataset, which is used to evaluate a model fit on the training dataset while tuning model hyperparameters. GridSearchCV from scikit-learn is applied to systematically go through multiple combinations of hyperparameters, cross-validating each one, and determine which one gives the best performance. After tweaking the XGBoost model several times, the study gets the optimal hyperparameters as follows:

Learning_rate: 0.27

Max_depth: 5

Min_child_weight: 3

N_estimator: 40

The adjusted hyperparameters are then applied to XGBoost model again to get the optimal predictive performance.

