5. Discussion

5.1 Findings in the extracted keyword features

This study contributes to the exploration of uncaptured house features in textual descriptions. Previous empirical studies hardly tried to extract London's housing characteristics from textual descriptions. Through DOC and TF-IDF to filter and sort of word frequencies and human-decision to classify keywords,  this study extracts the 25 house features most frequently mentioned by real estate agents and sellers in the London Zoopla property text descriptions, involving five aspects: property ownership, housing purchase chain, location characteristics, functional zonings, and some other housing attributes.

Property ownership and purchase chain are not physical characteristics of the property, but share-freehold and chain-free are frequently mentioned in the text description, implying that buyers and sellers are very concerned about these issues, which may potentially impact the property value.

A good location is another feature that is widely mentioned but does not belong to the property's physical characteristics. The seller's description often draws the buyer's attention with the convenience of public transportation, proximity to bus stations and transportation links, and proximity to local amenities.

Regarding the property's physical characteristics, people seem to be particularly interested in central heating, what floor the house is on,  and whether the room structure is en-suite. Parking is also a significant concern, mainly on whether there is a parking space and, if so, whether it is on-street or off-street parking.

Bedroom, reception, kitchen, and garden are the four frequently mentioned functional divisions of a property. Through sub-level classification, it is found that there are different concerns for different functional partitions. Gardens can be divided into many types, of which the rear garden is the most common. Orientation is one of the most talked about factors in gardens, with south or southwest facing appearing in garden descriptions. For reception rooms, the focus is usually on having good vision and light. Bright light and dual aspects are often among the positive modifiers associated with reception rooms. When describing the kitchen, sunlight and orientation become less important. Instead, the decoration style is often mentioned. Many sellers tend to describe their kitchens with adjectives like modern, stylish, and modern.

5.2 Interpreting results of models

Overall, the XGBoost model shows better predictive performance than the Lasso regression model, either with or without keyword features. The difference in R2 before and after adding keyword features also shows that the XGBoost model can capture the impact of keyword features to a greater extent. In general, XGBoost can explain about 10% more property data than the Lasso regression model. However, XGBoost can only show the importance of one variable according to the change in prediction error. Whether the effect is positive or negative is often unknown. For a better interpretation of the results,  Lasso and XGBoost should be combined to find common features and differences between the models.

5.2.1 The importance of spatial location and total area

Both model results underscore the importance of spatial location and total property area. In the XGBoost regression, the order of the top 5 important variables never change with or without the keyword feature: number of bathrooms, sub-region central, sub-region east, number of beds, and number of receptions. Two are location variables, and three are regional variables.

Although in the XGBoost model, both the central and eastern sub-regions have significant impacts on real estate values, the results of the Lasso regression model further explain the spatial disparity. In the Lasso regression, the sub-region central is consistently the most positively influencing variable compared to the other sub-regions. In contrast, the sub-region east has lower property prices than the other sub-regions.

In addition, the number of bathrooms, the number of beds, and the number of receptions are the first, fourth, and fifth important variables in the XGBoost model, respectively. All three variables are related to the total area of properties, as properties with more space generally tend to have more bathrooms, beds, and receptions. The correlation matrix also shows that these three variables are strongly correlated. Lasso regression shows that all three variables positively affect property values.

The property type of detached houses and studios can also demonstrate the important impact of home size on house prices. Both detached and studios are in the top 15 for feature importance in XGBoost. However, according to the supplemental information provided in Lasso's regression, the detached house positively impacts property values, while the studio has the most negative impact on property values. It is not difficult to understand. A detached house is a house that is not connected to any other building. It usually represents a low-density living environment, good privacy, and a large total area. It shows that the average size of a detached house in London is 883 sq ft (Mortgage Introducer, 2021). In contrast,  a studio is a large room combined with a living room, dining room, and bedroom. It is usually smaller in size.

5.2.2 Meaningful keyword features

Total area and spatial location information explain 60.8% and 68.7% of property values in the Lasso and XGBoost datasets. Therefore, the improvement of R2 by keyword features does not seem very obvious, and the overall R2 value increases by 0.5% and 2.5%, respectively. However, this does not exceed the expectations of the study. Most previous research has pointed to the importance of location, and the total size of a property is definitely related to the total price. The primary purpose of this study is not to expect that text housing features will significantly increase the prediction results. Instead, this study expects these keyword features to be the icing on the cake, making predictions more detailed.

Six keyword features are in the top 15 important variables in the XGBoost model: central heating, chain-free, good location, double bedroom, garden orientation, and ground floor. Each keyword feature occupies 1% to 2.5% importance in the overall model. It could regard as these six features contribute to the property value, while other keyword features may not have an apparent influence on the property value. Combined with Lasso regression, except for garden orientation, the other five keyword features negatively impact the property value.

Garden orientation is often a hot selling point in real estate advertisements, with south or southwest-facing gardens more attractive than any other type of garden (Eldron, 2018). As London is located at around 51° north latitude, plenty of sunlight is essential for the home (Bedford, n.d.). A south-facing garden maximizes the available sunlight. In addition, a south-facing garden means that the sun rises in the east and sets in the west, but not directly from the top of the garden, avoiding direct sunlight and making the sun softer. As a result, south-facing gardens command a premium when the property hits the market. However,  previous studies have hardly quantified the impact of south-facing gardens on houses. Most discussions about garden orientation and house prices exist only in the promotion of real estate agents. This study quantifies the impact of garden orientation and clearly shows that garden orientation positively affects house prices.

The ground floor is found to have a negative impact on the property value. Privacy and security are ills on the first floor. Many residences in London are close to shops and services, meaning many people will pass by the house. Living on the first floor means that the furnishings inside the house may be visible, and the owner needs to be more vigilant about burglary than on the upper floors. Also, traditional tenement buildings are not built with today's building materials and technologies, so traditional tenement buildings, especially the ground floor, will increase the risk of the damp year by year (Blair , 2019). For these reasons, properties on the ground floor are slightly less valuable than those on high floors. The small positive coefficient in the number of floors in Lasso regression may also demonstrate that people prefer to live on higher floors.

Extracted text features are expected to positively impact property values, since no real estate agent would use negative features for marketing properties. However, in addition to the ground floor, It is unexpectedly found that properties mentioned keywords such as central heating, chain free, good location, and double room are less valuable than properties that do not mention these keywords. One assumption is that cheap properties tend to use more descriptions to promote themselves. For example, while central heating and double rooms represent a good housing feature, they are so common in properties today that many might even bother to mention them. Central heating may have been a luxury when it first appeared in UK homes in the 1970s, but today only a small percentage of UK properties do not have central heating (BBC, 2009). To test this conjecture, we count the sum of the number of keyword features contained in each property record, and properties with more keyword features have higher scores. Table 5.1 shows the average property price and the proportion of six significant keyword features in each score level. A score of zero indicates that none of the 25 extracted textual features are mentioned in the cleaned bulleted description of these properties. A score of 9 means that nine textual features are mentioned in the cleaned bulleted description of these properties.

Table 5.1 The average property price and the proportion of significant  keyword features in each score level

This table validates our inference. As more text feature scores are obtained, the average property price does not rise but falls. The average property price dropped from £1,288,764 to £616,291 when the score increased from 0 to 9. At the same time, as the score increases, the probability of mentioning keyword features gradually increases. For example, only 35% of properties with a score of 1 mentioned location-related information, compared to 92% of properties with a score of 9. It suggests that cheaper properties place more emphasis on marketing themselves on location. A property that does not mention location does not mean it is in a poor location; maybe it just does not need to use location to attract buyers. It should also be noted that since this study extracts the most common keyword features based on DOC and TF-IDF word frequency, it indicates that most of the keywords for the cheap property are pretty common. For high-end properties, there may be some more targeted but not captured textual features.

5.3 Limitation and future developments

As mentioned above, this study found that the most common keyword features in property descriptions tend to be the marketing focus of cheap properties. However, for high-end properties, some unobserved keyword features still need to be further explored. The word frequency ranking and human decision-making process filtered out the most common words in property descriptions while ignoring massive niche keyword features. These keywords may be rarely mentioned, but they can be more representative and impact house prices. Therefore, future research can summarize and classify all vocabularies in a clean bullet description instead of selecting only some words with the highest frequency to extract textual features more comprehensively.

In addition to this, future studies could use more comprehensive datasets. The value of Zoopla property data is that it provides abundant textual descriptions, making it possible to extract housing feature information from texts. However, it can only provide very limited other housing information, such as the location and total price of a property. In this study, unfortunately, the property price per square meter is more important than the total price of a property. Since the total price of a property is destined to be affected by the total area,  the total area is always one of the most dominant variables. In contrast, the influence of other variables on the property value is diluted to a certain extent. The price per square meter can strip the impact of the total area on the price and better present the impact of keyword features. The Zoopla data does not provide the total area variable, and it can only be roughly estimated from the number of reception rooms, bathrooms, and bedrooms. That makes it difficult to calculate the property price per square meter. Therefore, future research could link Zoopla property data and House Price per Square Metre. One potential choice is the new property dataset that Chi et al.(2021) created. As introduced in previous sections, this dataset linked residential transaction records from Land Registry Price Payment Data (LR-PPD) and real estate data from the domestic Energy Performance Certificate (EPC) together, providing both house prices per square meter and a significant number of property attribute data.

6. Conclusion

In conclusion, this study explores unobserved housing characteristics from unstructured property advertising text and measures their impact on the property value. The study area is set in London, with the use of 2020 Zoopla property data. After a series of data processing and text cleaning processes, more than 100,000 property records are finally used for this analysis. This study uses NLP technology, especially DTM and TF-IDF, to filter the most frequently mentioned and concerned vocabularies in the property bullet description, and then supplemented by artificial decision-making, dividing keywords into 25 categories under five categories. These keyword features are converted into dummy variables to complement Zoopla property data. Finally, the machine learning methods Lasso and XGBoost regressions are used to construct prediction models with and without keyword features, respectively.

The XGBoost model has been tested to have better overall prediction performance than the Lasso regression model. However, since XGBoost cannot fully interpret the specific impact of features on housing prices, this study combines the two models to interpret the results jointly. This study has the following major findings: 1. House ownership and purchase chain, these house attributes that are not part of the physical characteristics of the house, are frequently mentioned in the property description; 2. There are different promotion focuses on the different housing keyword features in advertisements. The parking pays attention to type; The garden pays attention to the orientation; The reception room pays attention to light; The kitchen pays attention to the decoration style. 3. The total area and location of the property are two attributes that have a decisive impact on the overall housing price. 4. Six keyword features: central heating, no chain, good location, double bedroom, garden orientation, and ground floor, have a greater impact on housing prices than other keyword features. Among them, except for the garden orientation, the other five housing characteristics have a negative impact on housing prices. Through further analysis, this paper speculates that the most common keyword features in property descriptions tend to be the marketing focus of cheap properties.

